long_desc.thetext:
Created attachment 1207 Visual Studio with partial error parsing
Current qooxdoo build tools (ie generate.py) do not have any option to specify output error format. Diagnostic of generate.py output is pretty hard. Also it's hard to integrate qooxdoo build process in third party IDE such as Eclipse or Visual Studio to get error list direct in IDE and not search them manually.
What I suppose to see it's kind of option for generate.py (or separate option in config.json) like:
--error-format="%f(%l,%c): error %e: %m"
Output error format can be determined using predefined sequences:
%f - filename %l - file line %c - character in line %e - error code %m - erro message
I was trying to parse errors using kind of this batch hell http://pastebin.com/bQJYNr7Q and even got suitable results in VC output (see attachment) but this script could not parse multiline errors and not universal at all kind of errors.
Error formatting could make development of qooxdoo application much easier.
Thanx in advance.
As the reporter of the bug you get automatically notified, so no need to add yourself to CC.

(In reply to comment #2) > Current qooxdoo build tools (ie generate.py) do not have any option to specify > output error format. Diagnostic of generate.py output is pretty hard. Also it's > hard to integrate qooxdoo build process in third party IDE such as Eclipse or > Visual Studio to get error list direct in IDE and not search them manually. > > What I suppose to see it's kind of option for generate.py (or separate option > in config.json) like: > > --error-format="%f(%l,%c): error %e: %m" > > Output error format can be determined using predefined sequences: > > %f - filename > %l - file line > %c - character in line > %e - error code > %m - erro message
Interesting proposal. But I would first like to hear more about the underlying problem. What is "hard" with generator diagnostics? Which requirements do you face when integrating with Eclipse? Which with Visual Studio?
Your screenshot looks kind of ok to me, but I think this is due to your .bat processing?!
> I was trying to parse errors using kind of this batch hell > http://pastebin.com/bQJYNr7Q
Brave one ;-). I would do this in Python, why don't you?
> and even got suitable results in VC output (see > attachment) but this script could not parse multiline errors and not universal > at all kind of errors.
Ah, now you're getting at it. But the generator doesn't have multiline errors, does it?! Can you give an example of that? Do you mean that context is spread across multiple lines? Or do you think of exception messages, where the offending file is often printed on an extra line?
What do you mean with "universal kind of errors"?
Also, do you distinguish between warnings and errors?

(In reply to comment #2) > Brave one ;-). I would do this in Python, why don't you? That was just desperation :) and i'm not familiar with python.
> > and even got suitable results in VC output (see > > attachment) but this script could not parse multiline errors and not universal > > at all kind of errors. > > Ah, now you're getting at it. But the generator doesn't have multiline errors, > does it?! Can you give an example of that? Do you mean that context is spread > across multiple lines? Or do you think of exception messages, where the > offending file is often printed on an extra line? > > What do you mean with "universal kind of errors"? > Well generator outputs errors and warning in totally different formats. For example try to derive app/window qooxdoo class from unknown parent and you'll get warning without even file/line pointer.
> Also, do you distinguish between warnings and errors? Any output error contains at last two lines - first is error message and second - error pointer (thats why those batch script loosk so ugly - i was trying to get one error message from two lines). Also there is kind of errors when generator puts code samples in error messages and then error message may contain more than one line and also format is not clear. For example create class member like this:
multiline: "error',
And get kind of this error mrssage:
<class 'ecmascript.frontend.SyntaxException.SyntaxException'> : Unable to tokenize text starting with: ", function() { page1.show({ reverse: true }); }, this);
// Add the pages to the page manager. var manager = new qx.ui.mobile.page.Manager(false); manager.addDetail([ page1, pa" (mobileportal.Application:77) File: Z:\Projects\ODS\Mobile
It's not clear at all as you see and this is not copy/paste error.
And about "hard" diagnostics - it's just a metter of taste but i prefere to click on error message in error output window to open editor exactly at the error point to fix it but not scroll build output window (with HUGE amount of other messages), look for error or warning messages, then go to project layout, search for filename, click on it and just them then scroll/go to error point.
Anyway this feature will not change anything for those who do not need it :)

(In reply to comment #3) > (In reply to comment #2) > Well generator outputs errors and warning in totally different formats. For example try to derive app/window qooxdoo class from unknown parent and you'll get warning without even file/line pointer.
Please include concrete output samples. You shouldn't rely on us reproducing the output you find an issue. This might change over time and we want bugs to be self-documenting. In 6-12 months it should still be clear from the bug which concrete messages you find difficult.
> > > Also, do you distinguish between warnings and errors? > Any output error contains at last two lines - first is error message and second - error pointer (thats why those batch script loosk so ugly - i was trying to get one error message from two lines). Also there is kind of errors when generator puts code samples in error messages and then error message may contain more than one line and also format is not clear. For example create class member like this: > > multiline: "error',
Where did you put this line? In the 'members' section? Or in the top-level of a class map?
> > And get kind of this error mrssage: > > <class 'ecmascript.frontend.SyntaxException.SyntaxException'> : Unable to tokenize text starting with: ", function() { > page1.show({ reverse: true }); > }, this); > > // Add the pages to the page manager. > var manager = new qx.ui.mobile.page.Manager(false); > manager.addDetail([ > page1, > pa" (mobileportal.Application:77) > File: Z:\Projects\ODS\Mobile > > It's not clear at all as you see and this is not copy/paste error.
I see. It's supposed to be helpful when eyeballing the console output, to spot the code location from the context.
> And about "hard" diagnostics - it's just a metter of taste but i prefere to click on error message in error output window to open editor exactly at the error point to fix it but not scroll build output window (with HUGE amount of other messages), look for error or warning messages, then go to project layout, search for filename, click on it and just them then scroll/go to error point.
I can perfectly appreciate why you like IDE integration. But my question was what are your requirements for achieving this. Which interfaces do you have to fulfil? Which information has to be in a single line to be picked up, which doesn't?
I could see your proposal being implemented as a dedicated command-line switch, like e.g. "--terse-logging", that turns on a different kind of logging and honors format strings like you suggested. Then people can decide if they want "nicely" layouted console messages or those that are better machine-readable.

(In reply to comment #4)
> Please include concrete output samples. You shouldn't rely on us reproducing > the output you find an issue. This might change over time and we want bugs to > be self-documenting. In 6-12 months it should still be clear from the bug which > concrete messages you find difficult. >
Code: ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- qx.Class.define("mobileportal.Application", { extend: qx.application.Mobile2, ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Produces: ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- ........ >>> Collecting classes - Warning: mobileportal.Application (24,10): Unknown global symbol used: 'qx.application.Mobile2' ........ >>> Collecting classes - Warning: mobileportal.Application (24,10): Unknown global symbol used: 'qx.application.Mobile2' ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Warning message produced twice without filename.
> > multiline: "error', > > Where did you put this line? In the 'members' section? Or in the top-level of a > class map? >
Yes this is members section in Application.js
> > > > And get kind of this error mrssage: > > > > <class 'ecmascript.frontend.SyntaxException.SyntaxException'> : Unable to > tokenize text starting with: ", function() { > > page1.show({ reverse: true }); > > }, this); > > > > // Add the pages to the page manager. > > var manager = new qx.ui.mobile.page.Manager(false); > > manager.addDetail([ > > page1, > > pa" (mobileportal.Application:77) > > File: Z:\Projects\ODS\Mobile > > > > It's not clear at all as you see and this is not copy/paste error. > > I see. It's supposed to be helpful when eyeballing the console output, to spot > the code location from the context. >
Not so heplfull - try to figure out filename from this output. "File: Z:\Projects\ODS\Mobile" is exactly what generator outputs.
> I can perfectly appreciate why you like IDE integration. But my question was > what are your requirements for achieving this. Which interfaces do you have to > fulfil? Which information has to be in a single line to be picked up, which > doesn't?
My requirement is just well formatted error and warning output that can be correcly parsed by IDE. Depends on IDE this format can be changed, that's why i'm proposing to have some kind of options for this (ie environment variable, config or command line option). For example VS error format is "%f(%l,%c): error %e: %m" in one line. For Eclipse format could be specified in options (see http://stackoverflow.com/questions/5332849/parsing-lint-errors-in-eclipse for example) but it still needs to be unified for all errors and warnings. I believe there is other developers with IDE like NetBeans that will be happy with such functionality.
> I could see your proposal being implemented as a dedicated command-line switch, > like e.g. "--terse-logging", that turns on a different kind of logging and > honors format strings like you suggested. Then people can decide if they want > "nicely" layouted console messages or those that are better machine-readable.
Sure it's must be be optional. Also i guess life's too short to read console output :)

(In reply to comment #5) > (In reply to comment #4) > > > Please include concrete output samples. You shouldn't rely on us reproducing > > the output you find an issue. This might change over time and we want bugs to > > be self-documenting. In 6-12 months it should still be clear from the bug which > > concrete messages you find difficult. > > > > Code: > ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- > qx.Class.define("mobileportal.Application", > { > extend: qx.application.Mobile2, > ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- > > Produces: > ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- > ........ > >>> Collecting classes - Warning: mobileportal.Application (24,10): Unknown global symbol used: 'qx.application.Mobile2' > ........ > >>> Collecting classes - Warning: mobileportal.Application (24,10): Unknown global symbol used: 'qx.application.Mobile2' > ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- > > Warning message produced twice without filename.
In many generator messages, the class id is used rather a file name (like here 'mobileportal.Application'). In the scope of the build this class id maps unambiguously to a file.
The fact that a message is duplicated during a generator run is due to multiple jobs being run. As the jobs are independent of each other, each logs the warnings it encounters.

It's supposed to be helpful when eyeballing the console output, to spot > > the code location from the context. > > > > Not so heplfull - try to figure out filename from this output. "File: Z:\Projects\ODS\Mobile" is exactly what generator outputs.
The generator also logs "(mobileportal.Application:77)" which gives the class and line number.
> > I can perfectly appreciate why you like IDE integration. But my question was > > what are your requirements for achieving this. Which interfaces do you have to > > fulfil? Which information has to be in a single line to be picked up, which > > doesn't? > > My requirement is just well formatted error and warning output that can be correcly parsed by IDE. Depends on IDE this format can be changed, that's why i'm proposing to have some kind of options for this (ie environment variable, config or command line option). For example VS error format is "%f(%l,%c): error %e: %m" in one line. For Eclipse format could be specified in options (see http://stackoverflow.com/questions/5332849/parsing-lint-errors-in-eclipse for example) but it still needs to be unified for all errors and warnings.
This is still too much hand-waving to be directly useful ("well formatted", "can be correctly parsed", ...; remember that we have to sync your requirements with others). So let me try to summarize what I THINK are your requirements:
- Messages must be single-line. - It must contain a file path (relative? absolute?). - It must contain a line number. - It must contain a column number (character position in line). - It must contain an error number (we don't have those). - It must contain an error text. - It may contain other literal elements (parens, colons, fixed text, ...). - All these elements must be positioned freely in a final message, controlled by configuration (like a format string).
Is this what you need? Is this ALL that you need? - It still leaves some questions open, though:
- What about stack traces? Can they be included or need they to be excluded? - What about intervening text (headings, progress indication, ...)? Does it confuse IDE's? In other words: Need the formatted messages be the ONLY messages the generator produces in this mode?

> > The generator also logs "(mobileportal.Application:77)" which gives the class > and line number. > Can you explain this to Visual Studio please? :)
> This is still too much hand-waving to be directly useful ("well formatted", > "can be correctly parsed", ...; remember that we have to sync your requirements > with others). So let me try to summarize what I THINK are your requirements: > > - Messages must be single-line. > - It must contain a file path (relative? absolute?). > - It must contain a line number. > - It must contain a column number (character position in line). > - It must contain an error number (we don't have those). > - It must contain an error text. > - It may contain other literal elements (parens, colons, fixed text, ...). > - All these elements must be positioned freely in a final message, controlled > by configuration (like a format string). > > Is this what you need? Is this ALL that you need? - It still leaves some > questions open, though: > > - What about stack traces? Can they be included or need they to be excluded?
That's quit strange questions. For now i (just i!) need file, line and error message. But who knows what needed by other developers? I'm speaking not about exact output format and it's operands, but about a way (just an idea!) it could be specified and changed. If you'll implement optional error output formatting using kind of patterns described in my first message you'll able to get ALL listed requirements and MUCH MORE. List of available patterns and operands for formatting is up to you. And of course it must be as varied as possible!
If you still need real life example of how's done in other applications - check "man date" formatting section.
> - What about intervening text (headings, progress indication, ...)? Does it > confuse IDE's? In other words: Need the formatted messages be the ONLY messages > the generator produces in this mode?
That's another question because error and info messages splitted to different streams (stdout and stderr) such kind of output ---------- - Processing 2 locales \|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\| ---------- is meaningless for IDE but it's easy to redirect them to /dev/null.

Is this ALL that you need? - It still leaves some > > questions open, though: > > > > - What about stack traces? Can they be included or need they to be excluded? > > That's quit strange questions. For now i (just i!) need file, line and error message. But who knows what needed by other developers? I'm speaking not about exact output format and it's operands, but about a way (just an idea!) it could be specified and changed.
Experience shows that in order to implement something you need to settle for some (at least initial) set of properties of the solution. And I'd rather implement your concrete requirements than some fuzzy idea. Again, this might also need to be synchronized with requirements from other users that are complementary or even conflicting, so having a clear list of requirements in this bug is much appreciated. You have the chance here to say for example "But wait, VS expects an absolute path to the file, in order to locate it", because I will not try to figure that out (I don't even have acces to VS). If you don't, don't come back later to complain.
> If you'll implement optional error output formatting using kind of patterns described in my first message you'll able to get ALL listed requirements and MUCH MORE. List of available patterns and operands for formatting is up to you. And of course it must be as varied as possible!
As varied as possible is not implementable :). You can do a lot in favor of your bug if you provide precise information, motivation and requirements.
> > If you still need real life example of how's done in other applications - check "man date" formatting section.
I'm generally aware of format strings, that's not the issue.
> > - What about intervening text (headings, progress indication, ...)? Does it > > confuse IDE's? In other words: Need the formatted messages be the ONLY messages > > the generator produces in this mode? > > That's another question because error and info messages splitted to different streams (stdout and stderr) such kind of output > ---------- > - Processing 2 locales \|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\|/-\\|/-\| > ---------- > is meaningless for IDE but it's easy to redirect them to /dev/null.
So I take that to mean "no".

(In reply to comment #8) > Experience shows that in order to implement something you need to settle for > some (at least initial) set of properties of the solution. And I'd rather > implement your concrete requirements than some fuzzy idea. Again, this might > also need to be synchronized with requirements from other users that are > complementary or even conflicting, so having a clear list of requirements in > this bug is much appreciated. You have the chance here to say for example "But > wait, VS expects an absolute path to the file, in order to locate it", because > I will not try to figure that out (I don't even have acces to VS). If you > don't, don't come back later to complain.
IC. Ok, let's say this "should be enough for everyone":
- error format can be specified using option --error-format=<format> - error format can be specified as environment variable GEN_ERR_FORMAT or in "let" section of config.json - warning format can be specified using option --warning-format=<format> - warning format can be specified as environment variable GEN_WARN_FORMAT or in "let" section of config.json
where <format> is a printf-style formatted string where following optional operands may appear (in alphabet):
%a - qooxdoo class name (ie mobileportal.Application) %c - character number %C - error or warning code (if you'll ever have one in future) %d - date of error processed (format is an issue) %e - generation step (ie "Processing configuration", "Executing: build::build-script") %f - file name with absolute path %F - file name with relative path %i - any additional error infortation %l - line number %m - error or warning message text (must contain single line of text ie "file not found" etc) %n - file name without path %p - absolute file path %P - relative file path %s - code sample (may produce multiline output) %t - stack trace (may produce multiline output) %T - time of error processed (format is an issue) %u - timestamp of error processed (format is an issue)
Format may contain escape sequences such as \n, \r, \t with default behaviour. Errors and warnings must be passed to stderr.
Default error format (if no option were specified) is an issue but i propose this one as legacy:
"%m (pos (%l, %c))\nFile: %f"
Default warning format (if no option were specified) is an issue but i propose this one as legacy:
"- Warning: %a (%l, %c): %m"
Example for Visual Studio:
--error-format="%f(%l,%c): error %C: %m" or --error-format="%p\%n(%l,%c): error %C: %m"
> So I take that to mean "no". Yes.

You misunderstood me. I was not asking for the MAXIMUM requirements that "should be enough for everyone"; that's certainly nothing we would implement in a first step. But I asked the MINIMUM (yet precise) requirements to satisfy your concrete situation. But judging from your other comments this would be
> Example for Visual Studio: > > --error-format="%f(%l,%c): error %C: %m"
and that's what we're going to implement once we get to it (but in config, not as command line option).
